Raw dev notes -- Automating the "Missing Report" Hunt

Okay, so this past week was all about getting this little "missing report checker" script off the ground and actually useful. The project itself is pretty straightforward: we have this system (let's call it the "Matchmaker" system, to keep things generic) that's supposed to generate daily reports. Sometimes, for whatever reason, those reports just... don't show up. Historically, it's been a manual check, which is tedious and prone to human error. My goal was to automate that check, so we know immediately if a report is missing and can chase it down. Basically, save some headaches and ensure data integrity.

The initial commit was just getting the core logic working. I spent a good chunk of time figuring out how to connect to the Matchmaker system, pull the relevant data, and then compare it against what *should* be there. It's a lot of date manipulation and string matching, making sure I'm looking for the right report on the right day. Getting that first "Yep, report X for Y date is missing!" message to pop up was a small victory.

But, of course, a script that you have to manually run isn't much of an automation. So, the next big push was making it run on its own. First up, logging. Man, I always forget how crucial good logging is until I'm trying to debug something that's supposed to run in the background. I added file-based logging so I could see what the script was doing, when it ran, and if it encountered any issues, without having to babysit a console window. It's a simple thing, but it makes a world of difference for unattended processes.

Then came the actual scheduling. This was a bit of a rabbit hole. I explored a few options for how to trigger it, eventually settling on an "at-logon" task. It's not perfect, but for this specific use case, it works well enough. I even wrote a quick "trigger decision doc" for myself, just outlining why I chose that method over others (like a full-blown scheduled task service) and what the trade-offs were. It felt good to actually document my thought process for once, instead of just hacking it together.

The final piece for this sprint was adding email notifications for failures. Because what's worse than a script silently failing? A script silently failing that you *don't even know* is failing! I specifically targeted login errors (which can happen if credentials expire or the system is down) and general script crashes. Getting that SMTP setup right was a minor pain, but now, if something goes sideways, I'll get an email. It's a huge relief knowing I won't be blindsided by a week's worth of missing reports because the checker itself stopped working.

Honestly, this whole process felt like a mini-lesson in building a robust, operational tool, even for something relatively small. It's not just about the core logic; it's about visibility, reliability, and error handling. I felt a bit like an ops engineer for a few days, which was a cool change of pace. It reinforced that even simple scripts need a certain level of care if they're going to be truly useful and not just another thing to manually check.

Next up: refining the report output and maybe adding some more detailed error handling.
